  "prompt": "How I recover my Facebook password?",
  "response": "Okay, here's a comprehensive guide on how to recover your Facebook password, covering the most common scenarios:\n\n**1. Using the \"Forgot Password?\" Option:**\n\n   *   **Go to the Facebook Login Page:** Open your web browser and go to `www.facebook.com`.\n   *   **Click \"Forgot Password?\"**  This is usually located below the password field.\n\n   *   **Identify Your Account:**\n        *   **Search by Email or Phone Number:**  Enter the email address or phone number associated with your Facebook account in the provided field. Facebook will search for the account linked to that information.\n        *   **Search by Name:** If you don't remember your email or phone number, you can try searching by your full name and the name of a friend.  This method is less reliable but can work if you've provided accurate information on your profile.\n\n   *   **Choose a Recovery Method:**  Once Facebook finds your account, it will present you with several options for recovering your password:\n        *   **Send Code via Email:** A verification code will be sent to the email address associated with your account.\n        *   **Send Code via SMS:** A verification code will be sent to the phone number associated with your account.\n        *   **Use My Google Account:** (If linked) If you've previously linked your Google account to your Facebook account, you can use this to reset your password.\n        *   **Help from Friends:** (If enabled)  If you've set up trusted contacts, you can ask them for a recovery code.  *This feature is not widely used anymore.*\n\n   *   **Follow the Instructions:**\n        *   **Enter the Verification Code:**  Retrieve the code from your email or text message and enter it into the designated field on Facebook.\n        *   **Create a New Password:**  You'll be prompted to create a new, strong password.  Make sure it's different from previous passwords and difficult for others to guess.\n\n   *   **Log In with Your New Password:**  Once you've created a new password, you should be able to log in to Facebook.\n\n**2. If You No Longer Have Access to Your Email or Phone Number:**\n\n   This is a more challenging situation, but it's still possible to recover your account.\n\n   *   **\"No Longer Have Access to These?\" Link:**  After trying to reset your password and being prompted for a verification code to your old email or phone, look for a link that says something like \"No longer have access to these?\" or \"I don't have access to this email/phone.\"\n\n   *   **Alternative Email Address:** Facebook will ask you to provide an alternative email address where they can contact you.  Use an email address you currently have access to.\n\n   *   **Account Verification:** Facebook will likely require you to provide additional information to verify your identity. This could include:\n        *   **Uploading a Photo of Your ID:**  A government-issued photo ID (driver's license, passport, etc.) is the strongest form of verification. Make sure the name and photo on your ID match the information on your Facebook profile.\n        *   **Answering Security Questions:** If you previously set up security questions, you might be asked to answer them.\n        *   **Providing Information About Your Account:** Facebook might ask you questions about your friends, posts, or other activity to confirm you are the account owner.\n\n   *   **Wait for Facebook to Review:**  After submitting your verification information, you'll need to wait for Facebook to review your request. This can take a few days.  Check the alternative email address you provided for updates.\n\n   *   **Follow Facebook's Instructions:** If your verification is successful, Facebook will provide you with instructions on how to reset your password and regain access to your account.\n\n**3. If Your Account Was Hacked:**\n\n   *   **Report the Compromised Account:** If you suspect your account was hacked, you should report it to Facebook immediately. Look for a \"My Account Was Compromised\" or \"Report Hacked Account\" link on the login page or in the help center.\n\n   *   **Follow Facebook's Instructions:** Facebook will guide you through the process of securing your account, changing your password, and removing any unauthorized activity.\n\n**Important Tips and Considerations:**\n\n*   **Use a Strong Password:**  Create a password that is at least 12 characters long and includes a combination of uppercase and lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols. Avoid using easily guessable information like your birthday or name.\n*   **Enable Two-Factor Authentication:**  This adds an extra layer of security to your account by requiring a code from your phone or another device in addition to your password when you log in from a new device.  Enable this in your Facebook security settings.\n*   **Keep Your Email and Phone Number Up-to-Date:**  Make sure the email address and phone number associated with your Facebook account are current and accessible.\n*   **Avoid Phishing Scams:**  Be wary of emails or messages that ask for your Facebook password or other personal information. Facebook will never ask for your password via email.\n*   **Check Your Login History:** Regularly review your login history in your Facebook security settings to identify any suspicious activity.\n*   **Trusted Contacts (Less Common Now):** While less common now, if you've previously set up trusted contacts, they can still help you recover your account by providing recovery codes.\n\n**Troubleshooting:**\n\n*   **Incorrect Email/Phone Number:** Double-check that you are entering the correct email address or phone number associated with your account.  Typos are common.\n*   **Email in Spam/Junk Folder:**  If you're expecting a verification code via email, check your spam or junk folder.\n*   **SMS Delivery Issues:**  If you're not receiving the verification code via SMS, make sure your phone number is correct and that you have good mobile service.  Sometimes, SMS delivery can be delayed.\n*   **Facebook Help Center:** If you're still having trouble, consult the Facebook Help Center. Search for topics related to password recovery and account security.\n\n**In summary:**  Start with the \"Forgot Password?\" option.  If that doesn't work because you lack access to the associated email/phone, use the \"No Longer Have Access?\" link and be prepared to verify your identity with a photo ID.  Report a hacked account immediately.  And, most importantly, take steps to secure your account *after* you regain access (strong password, two-factor authentication).\n",
